HEADWORD: Inhesion
<hw>In*he"sion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>inhaesio</ets>. See <er>Inhere</er>.]</ety> <def>The state of
existing, of being inherent, in something; inherence.</def> <rj><au>A.
Baxter.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Constant <qex>inhesion</qex> and habitual abode.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inhiation</ent>⟦br⟧
